<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM23600 - Shares that may be awarded: General pre-emption provisions</h1>
<p>General pre-emption provisions must be tested:</p>
<ul>
<li>in cases with employee pre-emption restrictions, to ensure that the requirements of paragraph 33(3)(c) are satisfied (see <a href="ESSUM33570.htm">ESSUM33570</a>), and</li>
<li>in their own right to ensure that they attach to all ordinary shares in the same company (see <a href="ESSUM23475.htm">ESSUM23475</a>).</li>
</ul>
<p>For the purposes of paragraph 33(3) (c) the only significant difference which is permitted between the requirement to offer employee held shares and that relating to other shares of the same class is effectively that</p>
<ul>
<li>an employee is forced to sell when he ceases, whereas 	</li>
<li>other shareholders may withdraw their transfer notices if they decide against selling.</li>
</ul>
<p>The general pre-emption provisions usually appear first in the clauses of the Articles regulating transfers of shares.  The most common format is:</p>
<ul>
<li>any member (shareholder) wishing to sell or transfer shares gives the company a "transfer notice" indicating he or she wishes to offer their shares for sale</li>
<li>the company offers the shares to all other shareholders at a "fair value" determined by the company's auditors (see <a href="ESSUM23560.htm">ESSUM23560</a>)</li>
<li>if the shares being offered for sale are not all taken up by the other members, the vendor shareholder is usually given the opportunity to offer them to a person of his own choice.</li>
</ul>
<p>The employee pre-emption provisions (if there are any) then usually appear after the general pre-emption provisions and</p>
<ul>
<li>deem ceasing employees (and, usually, directors) to have given a transfer notice if one is not actually served within a specified period, and </li>
<li>apply all of the preceding general pre-emption provisions to such compulsory sales by employees and directors.</li>
</ul>
<p>Some Articles contain, as part of the general pre-emption provisions, the power to revoke a transfer notice once given.  This is acceptable for the purposes of general pre-emption restrictions under paragraph 30(1)(a). But care should be taken to ensure that a compulsory transfer notice served, or deemed to have been served, under the employee pre-emption procedures cannot be revoked. If employee pre-emption transfer notices are revocable the requirements of paragraph 33(3)(a) will not be satisfied (see <a href="ESSUM33500.htm">ESSUM33500</a>). </p>
<p>Some Articles contain an "all or nothing" provision in the general pre-emption provisions, such that if a buyer is not found for all of the shares being offered for sale, then none shall be sold.  This is acceptable for the purposes of general pre-emption, but care should be taken to ensure that it does not apply to the compulsory sales under the employee pre-emption procedures.  If buyers are only found for part of the holding of a ceasing employee, then that part of the holding must be transferred.</p>
<p>General pre-emption provisions for offering the vendor's shares to other persons may give priority rights (of first refusal) to certain shareholders. If there is more than one class of ordinary shares, other holders of the same class of share are normally given preference.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>‘A’ ordinary shares are to be offered first to other holders of ‘A’ ordinary shares, then to the holders of ‘B’, ‘C’ and ‘D’ ordinary shares in proportion to their existing shareholdings.</p>
<p>‘B’ shares are to be offered first to other holders of ‘B’ shares then to the holders of ‘A’, ‘C’ and ‘D’ shares in proportion.</p>
<p>There is no objection to this in principle for the purposes of paragraph 33(3), provided the same procedures apply for transfers by all shareholders, including employees and directors.  But the priority rights thereby given to other shareholders may need to be considered for the purposes of paragraph 30(1)(a) to ensure that they do not result in the eligible shares being restricted by having lesser rights in comparison (see <a href="ESSUM23475.htm">ESSUM23475</a>).</p>
